title: Grateful Dead Live at Moody Coliseum, S.M.U on 1977-10-15
description:
Set 1

Bertha-> Good Lovin', They Love Each Other, Mama Tried-> Big River, Ramble On Rose, Looks Like Rain, Peggy-O, Let It Grow

Set 2

Samson & Delilah, Sunrise, Terrapin Station-> Saint Stephen-> Not Fade Away-> Stella Blue-> Sugar Magnolia, E:Truckin'-> E: One More Saturday Night

reviews.review_text: Terrrapin > St. Stephen > NFA !!! The really unfortunate thing about this show is that the SBD recording is oversaturated and sounds horrible and nothing Dave could do could change that fact.  Adding the AUD makes it even worse.  It's a disaster all around.  But among the ruins of what could have been a classic show is the surprise 31:47 Terrrapin > St. Stephen > NFA run which, for some reason, isn't as badly oversaturated as the rest (thank goodness) - and smokes!  And Dave expertly fades in and fades out an AUD portion of a cut NFA that you gotta hear. If there was anything worthwhile in Mr. Usborne working on this show, it was seamlessly fixing NFA for our listening pleasure.   Thanks Dave.

St Stephen> NFA!!!!! My God in Heaven, the energy of this show. 
This is one of those underrated, unrecognized gems primarily due to the mediocre SBD. To append the complete idiot "lilrichwhiteboy" who posted below, sound quality snobs won't like it. The mix great, just a bit of a muddy recording.

Now, performance-wise Holy SHIT... This show is almost too intense for words. It's a great performance, especially the 2nd set. A GEM. And I'm sure the cocaine helped.

The first set is full of goodness. Let it Grow is the best I have ever heard. Incredible. 

Second Set- Just hold on to your fucking hats people....

St. Stephen>NFA is arguably the best of '77, maybe even ever. Probably my favorite NFA- tight, powerful, incredible energy among the whole band. The jam after the first verse of NFA is INSANE...it gets to that level where it's so intense that it isn't really music so much anymore. It's more just sonic spaceflight or something that only the Dead can achieve. Brilliant.
seriously listen to ST STEPHEN Wow Jerry just create a melody out of thin air and runs with it!   Throw in some power chords to build momentum and you have an amazing jam

Best copy of this wonderful show yet! I totally disagree with lilrichwhiteboy, that this is 'a disaster', ??? What? This is the best version of this show. The Bertha>Good Lovin is just crazy, Phil comes out the gate just thumping, and this Bertha has a unique feel to it, just 'in the pocket', and Jerry's solo on the good lovin is stunning. Every song smokes in the 1st set, finishing with a Let it Grow that stands with all the other excellent 77 versions. The 2nd set starts with yet another consistently powerful 77 Samson, and after Donna sings 'sunshine', the meat of the show - Terrapin>St. Stephen>NFA>Stella Blue>Sugar Mags>Truckin with a Saturday Night encore.. The St.Stephen is IMO one of the best ever.

holy crap losers complain about the sound. this show sounds great. solid matrix, good band mix, good room noise and great crowd.
this show blew me away. start to finish. i think this might be one of my all time favorite grateful dead shows. incredible performance and setlist. i was going to say which songs are some of my now all time fav performances but its all of them honestly. especially this sugar mag. best post 72 sugar mag hands down. 
excellent night vocally for everyone. jerry sounds fantastic. donna sounds AMAZING. bobby sounds fantastic. 
holy crap
6 stars
